{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_hines_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280659253/1927030201/0306.xml":{"full_text":"POORER TURKEYS\nj FLOODING MARKEI\nf*\nCrooked Breast and Cul\nStock Selling as Low as 30\ni. and 35 Cents Today.\nTurkey raisers are shipping theii\ncrooked breast turkeys and culls tc\ntho local market, apparently anxious\nto get rid of the stock they do not\nintend to carry over for this year's\nChristmas market. Price of such\nstock is far below that charged for\nfancy stock, according to market\nreports, there being no demand for\nI them. Such turkeys sold as low as\n80 and 35 cents today.\n\"Weather conditions the past few\ndays enabled raisers to ship dressed\nstock to market. There still .is a\nfairly good demand for choice turkeys,\nhotels and restaurants continuing to\nserve them. Choice dressed stock\nsold at 45 and 48 cents this morning,\nthe live ones bringing 40 and 42.\nDealers believe the low price has\n#>een reached in the egg market, price\nof current receipts remaining at 23\ncents. Reports of steady egg markets\nin the large cities in the East and\nWest suggest to local dealers that\nprices soon may advance.\nToday\u2019s Wholesale Prices.\nButter\u2014Fresh, 1-pound prints, 55a\n56: tub, 54a55; store packed, 30.\nEggs\u2014Fresh, selected, 25a26; hen\nnery, 28; current receipts, 23.\nPoultry, alive\u2014Turkeys, 40; chick\nens, 38a40: white Leghorns, 24a25;\nfowls, 27a 29; roosters. 20; ducks,\n208.23; keats. young, 65; old. 30a35.\nDressed \u2014Turkeys, 45; old toms, 40;\nfowls, 24a30; capons, fancy, heavy,\n35; smaller, 30a32; fowls, 28a30; keats,\nyoung, 60a70: old, 25a30; ducks, 28a30;\nchickens, 38a40.\nMeats \u2014Beef, nal7li; veal, 23a26;\nlambs, 28a30; fresh hams, 26a28:\n'\u2022shoulders, 21a22: loins, 28; smoked\nhams, 28a30; smoked shoulders, 18a20.\nLive stock\u2014Calves, choice, 15%;\nmedium, llal3; thin, 7a\u00df; lambs, 13.\nFruit and Vegetable Review.\nToday\u2019s market report on fruits and\nvegetables, compiled by the Market\nNews Service, Bureau of Agricultural\nEconomics, says:\ns Apples\u2014Supplies liberal; demand\nlight, market steady; barrels, Pennsyl\nvania, No. 1 Staymans, 3.00;\nboxes. Northwestern, medium to large\nsizes extra fancy winesaps, 2.75a3.00;\nbushel baskets, no sales reported.\nCabbage\u2014Supplies moderate; de\nmand moderate, market steady: new\nstock, South Carolina, 1%-bushel\nhampers pointed type, 1.25a1.50;\nf Florida, 1 %-bushel hampers pointed\nype, 1.50a1.75; ordinary quality and\ncondition low as 1.00; Texas, barrel\ncrates, approximately 100 pounds net,\nround type, 2.25a3.50.\nCelery\u2014Supplies limited; demand\nmoderate, market slightly stronger;\nFlorida, 10-inch crates, 1.75a3.00;\npoorer, 2.25a2.50; California, crates,\n5.00a5.75, few 6.00.\nLettuce\u2014Supplies moderate; de\nmand moderate, market steady; Cali\nfornia, crates, Iceberg type, 4-\u00a3 dozen,\n2.76a3.00.\nOnions\u2014Supplies moderate; de\nmand light, market firm; Ohio, 100-\npound sacks, Yellows, U. S. No. 1,\nmedium to large sizes, 2.75a3.00: poor\ner, low as 2.50; New York, 100-pound\nsacks, Yellows, U. S. No. 1, medium\nsize, 2.00a2.25; Michigan, 100-pound\nsacks, Yellows, U. S. No. 1, large size,\n3.25.\ni Potatoes\u2014Supplies liberal; demand\nmoderate; market fairly steady;\nMichigan, 150-pound sacks. Russet\nRural, U. S. No, 1. 3.65a3.75; Maine,\n120-pound sacks. Green Mountains,\nVs. S. No. 1, 3.00a3.2a; New York. 150-\npound sacks, Round Whites, U. S. No.\n1, 3.40.\nSpinach\u2014Supplies light; demand\nmoderate, market stronger; South\nCarolina, cloth-top barrels, Savoy\ntype, 2.50a2.75, mostly 2.50; Virginia,\nNorfolk section, bushel baskets, Savoy\ntype, wide range quality and condi\ntion, 50a90, few 1.00.\nStrawberries\u2014-Supplies light: de\nmand light, market steady; Florida,\npony refrigerators, Missionarys, 35;\npoorer as low as 25 per quart.\nString beans\u2014Supplies very light;\ndemand light, market steady; Florida,\n%-bushel hampers, green, 5.00a5.50.\nTomatoes\u2014Supplies light; demand\nlight, market steady; Florida, sixes,\nripes and turning wrapped, fancy\ncount, 4.50a5.00; choice count, 3.50a\n4.00; few good quality and condition,\nfancy count, 5.50.\ns NORMAL FORCES WORKING.\nST. PAUL, March 2 (Special).\u2014The\nworst part of the quiet industrial sea\n\u2022on is over in this section and normal\nforces are now working in packing\nplants, shoe factories and other indus\ntries.\nWABASH DIVIDEND.\nNEW YORK, March 2 (A ).\u2014A divi\ndend of $5 a share has been declared\n\u00abn the preferred \u201cB\u201d stock of the\nWabash Railway for the year 1926,\npayable April 1, to stock of record\nMarch 19.\n\nPIG IRON HIGHER.\nNEW YORK, March 2 (/\u00a5*).\u2014Bes\nsemer Pig Iron has been advanced 50\ncents a ton in the Pittsburgh district\nto 119.50. Quotations for No. 2 foun\ndry are $18.50 and basic, $lB.\nGERMAN BONDS AND STOCKS.\n(Quoted in dollar* per million marks.)\nBid. Asked\ng*rf,t <w In) 5s 1014-18. 1475.00 1650.00\nHamhurir 4 >4# 1010 06.00 105.00\n(Quoted in dollars ner thousand marks.\u00bb\n\u2022Germ Gen E!e<- 4 1 4* t>rp-w 27 00 29.00\nGarni Gen E'er 4Vi* 1810. 2 00 3.00\nBerlin 4\u00ab ore-war 500 600\nHambir 3* 3V4s 4s ore-w 2 00 2.50\nHamb-Anierti an Line 4 Vis 20.00 31 00\nNorth German Lloyd 4 >4s 27.00 20.00\nNorth German Lloyd 13.25 14 25\nPrussian Consols 3'As 1.40 1 00\nKrupn 5, 1821... 1.25 1.73\nPusseldorf 4s pie-war 3.00 6.00\nFrankfort a M 4s nre-war.. 4.00 6.00\nMunl' h 4s ore war 300 500\nRadisohe Atiilin 145.00 165 00\nAEG (German G. E.). 39.00 41.00\nAEG 'Germ (,en Elec! of 12 oft 13,00\nCommerr, and Privat Bank. .30.00 32.00\nDi*conto Gellachaft 65 00 67 00\npresdner Bank 33.00 35 00\nDeutsche Bank 45.00 47.00\nTint mstaedter Bank 65.00 67.00\nMerr-nr Bank Vienna...... .80 100\nHe.rden Chemical 11.0(1 13.00\nAustrian A E t (Gen Elect 1.00 1 25\nBerliner Handels 130.00 140.00\nDIVIDENDS.\nPe Pay- Hdrs. of\nRate. rind. able. Record.\nAm. Can nf 1 <J Apr. 3 Mar. 16\nAm. Car A Fdy.St.sn Q Apr. 1 .Mar. 11\nDo of $1.75 Q Apr. 1 Mar. 11\nAm. Woolen pf .1 s* 0 Anr 15 Mar. 11\nArkansas Nat Gas I2e O Apr. 1 Mar. 8\nBankers- Trust 5 Q Mar, 28 Mar. 11\nG Sp? Bnuir pf 2 V Apr. Mar. 10\nCambria Iron Co. $1 SA Apr. 1 Mar. 15\nCoca Cola Co 100 Btk Apr. 25 Alar. 18\nCom. Invest. Trust. 800 Q Apr. 1 Mar 15\nDo fikd pf IN Q Apr. 1* Mar. 15\nDo pf 1 K Q Apt. 1 Mar. 15\nDetroit. Sr (\"lev. Nav 2 Q Apr. l Afar. 15\nGeneral Bak A $1.25 Q Apr 1 Atar. 19\nHercules Powder ~2 O Mar. 25 Atar. 15\nLeh. Val Coal Sales $2 Q Anr. 1 Alar. 17\nLoew\u2019s Inc 50c Mar. 31 Mar. 19\niTfe Sayers 40c O Anr, Mar. 14\nMack Trucks $l5O Q Mar 31 Mar. 15\nDo Ist pf $176 Q Alar. 31 Mar. 15\nDo 2d pf $1.75 O Afar. 31. Mar. 15\nWfanh. Els- Sup $1.25 O Apr. 1 Mar. 21\nMar Ry mod ftd.sl 25 Q Apr. -1 Afar. 15\nMar land Oil $1 Q Mar. 31 Mar 19\nPattno M A Entr 4.1 Mar. 15 Mar. 10\nPave Dt Mtr pf $1 75 Q Apr. 1 Mar. 15\nPender (David) Gro\npf A 87He Q Mar. 1 Feb. 25\nPierce Arrow pf $2 0 Apr. 1 Mar. 15\nDr Cr of Cn Ist nf.l H O Apr. 15 Mar. 31\nSmith How Pa Mi pf 2 Q Apr 11 Mar. 31\nSou Car Pwr pf Ik O Apr. 15 Mar. 25\n9 W, Penn Pipe. .$1 Q Apr. 1 Mar. 15\nvickera Ltd pf. :7.s\u00ae\u00bb\nDo preference. 5\nWestern Electric.s2.6o Q Mar. 31 Mar. 2d\nMEN AND MONEY\nP By M. S. Rukeyter.\n(Copyright. 1827.)\nIrrespective) of political arrange\nments, Americans are becoming world\nminded to an increasing extent.\nII Dollars are being exported without\n11 regard to national boundary lines to\n(places that seem to offer the great\nest return.\nIn the last two years the bull, or\nrising, markets in security prices in\nGermany have been an outstanding\nfeature of the world financial situa\ntion.\nr What country will be the next great\n0 center, of speculation?\nThe answer to this question is in\n8 the future, but it is interesting that\nt numerous financiers who have taken\ns profits on their Teuton speculations\nare switching to French stocks.\nLarge quantities of equities in\nr French enterprises are being Imported\nt to this country and to other lands\nr outside of France. Incidentally, this\nmovement of securities provides\ns France with new capital in lieu of\nforeign loans, which are temporarily\nv interdicted in the London and New\n.1 York markets.\nraving Way for Revival.\no A shrewd economist, who has studied\nv the French economic situation closely,\nin conversation with me, said: \"France\nhas gone far toward placing its\u2019finan\ns cial house in order. The temporary\nhard money depression has had the\n3 effect of curtailing imports and domes\ns tic production. As a result, the\ni French people have been using up\nt accumulated supplies, thus paving the\nway for a business revival.\n\u201cOs all French equities, I prefer\nbank stocks. The large banks aunng\nt the earlier shrinkage in the exchange\nvalue of the franc protected them\nselves by keeping large balances\nabroad in stable currencies. They are\nnow in a position to recall those de\nposits and take advantage of oppor\ntunitles in domestic lousiness. I also\nlike French electrical companies, and\nalso public utilities.\"\nSome of the large houses have agen\noies abroad, searching for opportuni\nties in various classes of French\nstocks, including industrial issues.\nItaly is also being closely watched by\nforeign financial interests,\ni Having made interallied government\ndebt settlements with England and\nthe United States, Italy has access to\nloans in New York and London. Con\nsiderable Italian financing is now be\ning arranged in the American market.\n1 Germany is about two years ahead\nof France on the program back to\n1 economic normalcy.\nl Italy Moving likewise.\nFrance and Italy are moving some\nwhat together, although subject to\n5 widely varying problems.\nHaving emerged from the severe la\nbor troubles of last year, England is\nmaking progress toward recovery, and\nr the trade outlook there is more rose\n-1 ate than it has been at any time since\nj the signing of the armistice.\nGermany is imitating American busi\nness more closely than any other Eu\n-1 ropean country.\nNo other Old World nation has sent\nmore engineers to this country re\n-1 cently to study the technique of mass\nproduction than Germany.\nThe Germans were shrewd enough\nto perceive that the American system\nof mass production rests on a base of\nmass consumption.\nAccordingly, Germany in recent\nyears has gone In for the American\nsystem of financing consumption\nthrough installment plan schemes.\nThe New German System.\nIn Germany new elements have been\nl added to the scheme of financing con\ni sumers. So-called consumers\u2019 banks\nI have been organized. These banks lend\npurchasing power to borrowers, who\nreceive a special form of check book.\n1 With this credit the purchaser may\nbuy from any of the merchants com\nprised in the combination up to the\nlimit of the grant. The customer\nusually makes a moderate cash pay\nment and pays the remainder in credit\nchecks. On presenting the check to\nthe credit institution the merchant re\n-1 ceives within three days the full cash\n1 amount less expenses for collection.\nr The merchant is thus relieved of\nfinancing cares, and the consumer is\nindebted only to the finance company.\nThe consumers\u2019 banks In Germany\nplay a role similar to that of the\nAmerican finance companies, who buy\nthe promissory notes of partial pay\nment buyers of automobiles and other\nproducts. However, the German sys\ntem has made still easier the system\nof buying now and paying later.\nThe German system is expensive to\nthe consumer, who must pay about 20\nper cent for the accommodations.\nTHE BUSINESS OF GETTING\nAHEAD.\nWhat Makes for Leadership?\nThe will to lead is as important a\nquality for leadership as the capacity\nto lead.\nEarly success, though it may turn\nthe head of the weak-minded, is a\ngreat help to the strong and intelli\ngent, for it creates a habit and an at\ntitude of mind.\nIf morons, misfits and mediocre in\ndividuals are eliminated, the observer\nof men in business discovers that\nthose of fairly equal ability are fre\nquently distributed In Jobs varying\nsignificantly in rank and importance.\nSome men of genuine native ability\nare laggards because they are con\ntent to be second rale men.\nOthers of equal mentality and\nequipment rise far above them\nbecause of a flaming urge to reach\nthe top.\nEfficacy of Wishing.\nWilliam James, the philosopher, be\nlieved in the efficacy of wishing. \u201cIn\nalmost any subject,\u201d he wrote, \u201cyour\npassion for the subject will save you.\nIf you only care enough for a result,\nyou will almost certainly attain it. If\nyou wish to be rich, you will be rich;\nif you wish to be good, you will be\ngood. Only you must, then, really\nwish these things, and wish them\nwith exclusiveness, and not wish at\nthe same time a hundred other in\n1 compatible things Just as strongly.\u201d\nFirst rate men have faith in them\nselves. They have the courage of their\nconvictions. They belieA\u2019e that busi\ni ness problems are soluble and set out\nto find the answers to them. They are\nrestless and eager to lead. If their\ni ambition is backed by competence,\nthey come to the top, and constitute\nthe creative leaders of business.\nOthers, who Mould show up Just as\nwell in an intelligence test, are more\nbackward. They distrust themselves.\nThey magnify their limitations and\nminimize their mental and moral as\nsets. They shrink from responsibility,\nand are content to take orders from\nf others. They prefer security in their\n4 mediocre jobs to the zest of combat\nJ for first honors.\nHas Sense of Perspective,\nl The business leader is capable of\nJ visualizing the problems and oppor\nh tunities of the enterprise as a whole,\ni lie also has a sense of perspective; a\nfV'iir for rejecting unimportant de\nv tails and for concentrating his ener\ngies on what is significant. He al\nways has more ideas than lie can\ni) work out himself, and, therefore, is\nable to fertilize the imagination of\nthose who come in contact with him.\na The able business leader knows his\ni job.\n5 lie has the graciousness of manner\nt) to commend a subordinate for good\n5 work and the decency to criticize an\nemploye only in private.\n5 The leader is able to lay out and\narticulate the policies of a business en\nterprlse, and, though giving his em\n-3 ployaa latitude In the performance of\ntheir particular duties, .be makes sure\n8 that every one\u2019s activijjes are within\nTHE EVENTYG STAR. WASHiyOTOfT, P. 0., WEDNESDAY MARCH 2,195 T.\nRISE IN DIAMOND\nPRICE PREDICTED\nI-\nl Louis Cartier Sees Precious\nGems as Good Investments\nr\nl at Present.\nt. BY ,J. C. KOYLF.\nSpecial Dispatch to The star.\nI NEW YORK, March 2.\u2014America\nl was largely responsible for the big\ns South Africa diamond rush in the\nj Lichtenburg district, which got out of\n1 hand and necessitated cancellation of\ni all the claims located and resulted in\nannouncement that the government\nf would hold another \"rush\u201d Friday.\nr America already holds a very large\nr part of the world\u2019s precious stones\nand jewels. In addition, Americans\nare buying more than a hundred\nmillion dollars\u2019 worth of jewels each\n1 year.\nCustoms receipts show that $40,-\n000,000 worth of diamonds, are\nbrought here each year. This valu\nation does not include the duty on\nthe stones, nor include cutting,\nmounting or setting. With this huge\ndemand, America is the dominant\ni factor for the moment in the dia\nmond markets of the world.\nIt is a question, says Louis Car\ntier, well known Parisian jeweler now\non a visit here, where the future\nsupply of stones will come from.\nSoviet Treasures Sold.\n\"The Soviets have sold all their\ntreasures,\u201d he said, \"and the best\nexamples of precious stones have\nalways come from the old mines now\nbeing w'orked out. t foresee a large\nrise in the price of precious stones\nin a short time, due to the fact that\nthe floating supply of old stones is\nexceedingly small and rests in the\nhands of existing firms. There is\nno doubt that diamonds, pearls,\nemeralds, very large rubles and sap\nphires are always in great demand\nj *nd will, as they have for a long\ntime, dominate the fashion in Jewelry.\n\"America is destined to become the\ngreat international art center within\nthe next 25 ynirs. Almost all great\nart creations have flourished in a field\nt of gold. That is what the United\nBtates is today. Spain was the center\nin the fifteenth and sixteenth cen\nturies when the riches of the world\nwere pouring into Spanish coffers.\nFrance in the seventeenth century\n1 and England in the eighteenth wit\nnessed the flourishing of art coinci\ndent with national power and wealth.\n1 It is now America\u2019s great opportuni\nty to produce through its painters,\nsculptors, poets, goldsmiths or jew\n-1 eler craftsmen.\u201d\nNo small part of the precious stones\nin America are bought with the idea\nof convertible wealth in mind. Ip\nmany circles jewels take the place of\nsavings accounts, and represent a se\ncurity readily convertible into cash.\n1 Then, too, among a certain number, a\ndiamond is the concrete symbol of\nfinancial prosperity and success, and\noften Is the first thing bought to sig\nnify to the owner as well as to out\nsiders a change and Improvement in\nstatus. Engagement rings alone pur\nchased in 1927 will undoubtedly repre\nsent two scores million dollars.\nProtection Great Expense.\nThe protection of precious stones\nentails a tremendous expense for\nevery nation in the world, for jewels\nare held responsible for more crimes\nthan any other form of wealth. From\nthe day the rough stone is picked\nfrom the gravel or wrenched from an\noyster shell, it is guarded. Workmen\nare searched inside and out, the X-ray\nsimplifying the former investigations.\nNo small part of the duties of the\ncustoms officers of the world are de\nvoted to preventing jewel smuggling,\nwhile if jewels were non-existent the\npolice forces of most cities might be\ncut in half.\nDiamonds have never gone out of\nstyle, but the style of diamond cut\nting and setting varies as rapidly as\nthe designs of women\u2019s millinery. The\npresent vogue tends toward the long\nfour-cornered designs or to square\ncut diamonds.\n\u201cThe jeweler is the slave of the\ndressmaker,\" M. Cartier concluded,\n\u201cfor he creates for the dressed, not\nthe undressed woman. But neverthe\nless he can act independently and go\nto the arts for his inspiration whether\nthat art Is of the past or of the mod.\nem jazz-skyscraper type.\"\nFIRM REORGANIZED.\nNEW YORK, March 2\nganization of the American Writing\nPaper Co., lias been completed and\nthe new company has begun to\nfunction. Sidney L. Willson, presi\ndent, said the new company has re\ntained 16 of the 26 mills and will con\nfine its operations to these mills, all\nbut two of which are In Holyoke,\nMass. The others will be sold.\nthe range of the policies of the busi\nness.\nThe real leader gives orders in a\nmanner that Inspires instead of of\nfends.\nHe encourages his subordinates to\nenvisage themselves as intelligent co\noperating human beings, not mere\n\u201chands.\u201d\nThe leader seeks a market for lead\nership, and usually finds one. He is\nnot satisfied to play second fiddle\nonce he has wielded the conductor\u2019s\nbaton.\nThe leader appraises his business\nworth at a high figure, and is able to\nInduce the market to sanction his\nown appraisal.\nMother is\nil AlaraipJt\n\u2022\u2022Hoavomf Not a Drop!\" iTJMtI IIICU\u00ab\ni pONSTIPATION, biliousness, coated tongue, feverish\nV-/ headache, sick stomach-then is the time when mother\nrelies upon Dr. Caldwell\u2019s Syrup Pepsin. \u201cMy son had\nbeen constipated and bilious since birth. At the age of five he had\nsuch an attack of sour stomach and bad breath I had to take him\nput of kindergarten. It was then I gave him Syrup Pepsin. He\nimproved from the first dose and soon was back to school completely\nrestored and healthier than he had ever been before. It is a great\nf 0 to have a medicine for children in which we can have such\nlmpucit confidence. (Name and address sent on request.) i\nWitts Confidence of Old Folks\nS Ojd people are chimed by the gentle, kindly action\nof Dr. Caldwell s Syrup Pepsin. No pain, gripe or\ndepressing flushing of the bowels. Just an easy II\n1 movement and the fine feeling of restful comfort.\nThere s seldom any real sickness in the home that fflHMffll\nt Jeams to use Syrup Pepsin at the first sign of coated\ntongue, fever, biliousness, headache and such troubles 1 *t \u00abo\u00ab h J|\ni due to constipation. Recommended in a million DrGMmll w\nhomes. Sold by all druggists.\nFor a free trial bottle tend name and addreu to \u2022\u2022WJMr\ni Popiin Syrup Company, MonUceUo, Illinois PEPSIN I\nDEFICIT IS SMALLER.\nB. f C. A. January Report Shows\nI Improvement Over Last Year.\nSpecial Dinpati'h to The Star.\nBALTIMORE, March 2- The Janu\nary report of the Baltimore, Chesa\npeake and Atlantic Railway Co., which\nalso operates boats on two bay lines.\n5 shows improvement as contnrsted vrith\nthe corresponding month of 1925.\nRailway operating revenues, totaling\n$71,095. were $7,811 higher than in Jan\nuary, 1925, and although not railway\noperating income showed a deficit of\n$32,991 this was smaller by $9,989 than\nthe deficit shown for January of the\npreceding year.\nSavings were effected principally in\nmaintenance of equipment.\ni RAILROADS TO TORN\nTO STOCK ISSUES\ni\nj Carriers' Money Troubles\n1 Clearing\u2014so-50 Bond and\nShare Status Sought.\ni\nJ By the Associated Press.\nNew York. March 2.\u2014The barom\neters of Wall Street show reassur\ning signs of the clearing up of the\nmoney troubles that have beset the\nr railroads of the country in the last\ndecade. This statement was made\nyesterday by Robert K. Binkerd, vice\nchairman of the committee of ppfclio\nrelations of the Eastern railroads, -;tnd\naffirmed by a prominent railroad\nbanker. The latter said that 1927 wfll\nmark the turn in rihe financial lane\nthat leads to tho issuance of stock in- 1\nstead of bonds to met the carriers\u2019\nt necessities.\nIt is learned that eight of the big\ntransportation systems arc considering\nbroadening their stock issues. Tho\nrailroads are; Pennsylvania, LouisviHe\nand Nashville: Baltimore and Ohio,\nAtchison, Topeka and Santa Fe, Union\nI Pacific, Delaware and Hudson, Dela\nware, Lackawanna and Western and\nNashville, Chattanooga and St. Louis.\nC. O. Is a Leader.\nT Already the Chesapeake and Ohio\nj with an issue of $59,000,000 and the St.\nLouis and San Francisco with $17.-\n000,000 of common stock have led the\nway in the new movement of owner\nship emissions. The New York Cen\ntral has authorized a $100,000,000 stock\nr issue, with $20,000,000 reserved for\nemployes.\nWith some $7,000,000,000 to be pour\ned out into investment channels this\nyear, bankers feel that the time has\nt come for railroad stocks to be offered\nto the investing public. Increased\nearnings and an ability to improve\ni their situation through their own ef\ni forts has created a feeling of confl\ndence, bankers say, in partnership se-\nP curlties of railroads. For more than\n10 years the carriers, with hat in\nhand, have had to beg for money,\nl which could only be obtained bv bond\nIssues that created a heavy indebted\n-1 ness and a top-heavy capital struc\nture.\nHope for 50-50 Proportion.\ni Railroad officials and bankers hope\nto establish over a period of years\na capital structure for the carriers\nthat will show stocks and bonds in\n50-50 proportion. Then-e have been\nno stock issues of Importance in the\nlast 10 years except two preferred\nIssues of the Illinios Central and the\nChesapeake Ohio. Os nearly $3,000,-\n000,000 of railroad securities issued\n1 in the six years ending 1925, 90 per\ncent consisted of bonds and other\n1 forms of indebtedness.\n1 Mr Binkerd said the ultimate aim\not the railroads is to correct their\nstructures so that bonds and\nwfll be of even amounts,\nvve have been trying to avoid in*\ncreasing the funded debt,\u201d said sJVfr.\nBinkerd, \"and have been scraping the\nbarrel of all our resources. This year\nIoo v k\u00df to b e th first year in which a\nsubstantial step will be taken in that\ndl r\u00abctlon. Increased confidence in\nrailroad stocks has come because the\nrailroads have demonstrated their abil\n;L y *\u00b0J\u2122v Pr ove their own situation\nthrough their own efforts.\nTaken From Earnings.\nSince 1920 the railroads have ex\npended $6,000,f100,000 on equipment and\nimprovements and this money has\ntaken rom earnings and depre\nelation and retirement allowances,\nvv e have been stowing away the stock\n*\u2019\u00b0kfe.r\u00df money all these years and\nnow the time is coming when we must\nreturn to the stockholder the fruits of\nhis denial of dividends.\nBl i lke^ d tho Proportion of\nstock to bonds of the carriers was, at\nkst s'ear, 43.2 for stock\nand 66.8 for bonds. The tendency\ntoward the unbalance was first noted\nin 1910 when confidence in the rail\nroads began to bo undermined by\nabuses with resultant political attacks.\nend ca Pifal structure\ncountry\u2019s railroads stood $12,-\n380,000 000 in bonds and $9,419,000,000\nIn stocks.\nMr. Binkerd said that the Higher\nyield on railroad stocks would aid In\nbringing larger numbers into the fam\nily of railroad owners.\nNET REVENUES LARGER.\nBALTIMORE, March 2 (Special).\u2014\n1 Total telephone revenues of the Chesa\npeake Potomac Telephone Co. for\nJanuary amounted to $1,022,780 30 as\n1 compared with $1,045,356.82 in Decem\nber, 1926, and with $955,248.35 in Jan\nuary of that year, according to the\nmonthly report of the Public Service\nommission. Net telephone revenues\n1 amounted to $232,714.05 for January,\n1 as against $222,604.87 in December\nlast And $205,985.19 In January, 1926.\nCOTTON ADVANCES\nON FOREIGN NEWS\nI\